Introduction¶

The aim of this notebook is to demonstrate the process of training a Neural Network to extract the position of a particle from an image.

It will only consider images containing a single particle.

The stages are as follows:

  • Generate a set of synthetic images: Training, Validation and Test Sets
  • Define a DataLoader for this training data.
  • Load our Neural Network architecture and train the network
  • Use the trained network to extract the position of particles in the test set
  • Evaluate the accuracy of the extractions
  • (consider hyperparameters)

Generate Training, Validation, and Test Sets¶

Particle parameters¶

Define the distributions to be used for the particles that will be used when generating a set of training, validation and test images. Based on values extracted from Helgadottir, Argun, and Volpe (2019) and the source code accompanying that paper.

Position¶

Position of particle lies within a normal distribution with mean 0 and stdev 0.4, clipped to a minimum of -1 and maximum of +1

def positionDist(N=1):
    return np.clip(np.random.normal(0., 0.4, N),-1,1)

Radius¶

Radius of particle drawn from uniform distribution with minimum of 1.5 and maximum of 3

def radiusDist(N=1):
    return np.random.uniform(1.5,3,N)

Bessel Order¶

A random int between 1 and 3

def besselDist(N=1):
    return np.random.randint(1,3,N)

assert len(besselDist()) == 1
assert len(besselDist(3)) == 3
assert np.isin(besselDist(),[1,2,3])

Intensity¶

Can be positive or negative. Drawn from uniform distribution between .2, and .6

def intensityDist(N=1):
    return np.array([x[0]*x[1] for x in zip(np.random.choice([-1, 1],N), np.random.uniform(.2, .6, N))])

assert len(intensityDist(10))==10
assert len(intensityDist())==1

Image parameters¶

Define the distributions relating to image parameters. Values extracted from Helgadottir, Argun, and Volpe (2019) and the source code accompanying that paper.

SNR¶

The signal-to-noise ratio for the image is drawn from a uniform distribution between 8 and 80.

def snrDist(N=1): return np.random.uniform(8,80,N)

Background: level, gradient intensity and direction¶

  • The background level is drawn from a uniform distribution between 0.2 and 0.8.
  • The gradient intensity is drawn from a uniform distribution between 1 and 3.
  • The gradient direction is drawn from a uniform distribution between -180 and 180 (degrees)
def backgroundLvlDist(N=1): return np.random.uniform(0.2,0.8,N)
def gradientIntensityDist(N=1): return np.random.uniform(1,3,N)
def gradientDirectionDist(N=1): return np.random.uniform(-180,180,N)

Define Torch DataLoaders¶

DataLoaders are a key concept in Torch. On top of that Fastai layers Specific data loaders for different types of problems. We want to leverage those. But first we have to transform our inputs (to pixel co-ordinates) and into a pytorch Tensor.

First load in the groudtruth of particle positions that we saved when generating the images.

import pickle
from pathlib import Path

imagepath=Path('../images/')
raw_groundtruth = pickle.load(open(imagepath/'ground_truth.pkl', 'rb'))
print("This first 5 items:")
list(raw_groundtruth.items())[:5]

This first 5 items:

[('0000.png', (51, 0.5978850768277283, -0.4678342261785602)),
 ('0001.png', (51, 0.42130567012504017, 0.4002659922521066)),
 ('0002.png', (51, 0.21647210707942804, -0.479343098335002)),
 ('0003.png', (51, 0.07325943593197394, 0.0866462918120064)),
 ('0004.png', (51, 0.4088320998353721, -0.4270557647731041))]

And this is the transform we need to do: convert particle positions to pixel positions and reverse order so position in (y,x).

import torch

def scaledTensor(r,scale=True):
    h=r[0]//2
    if scale: return torch.Tensor([h+h*r[2],h+h*r[1]])
    else:     return torch.Tensor([r[2],r[1]])

groundtruth = {itm:scaledTensor(raw_groundtruth[itm],scale=True) for itm in raw_groundtruth}
print("This first 5 items:")
list(groundtruth.items())[:5]

This first 5 items:

[('0000.png', tensor([13.3041, 39.9471])),
 ('0001.png', tensor([35.0066, 35.5326])),
 ('0002.png', tensor([13.0164, 30.4118])),
 ('0003.png', tensor([27.1662, 26.8315])),
 ('0004.png', tensor([14.3236, 35.2208]))]

We can now build a data loader which puts together the images with the 'labels' - in this case the ground truth positions of the particles that we stored in a separate files during the image generation.

import fastai
from fastai.vision import *

data = (PointsItemList.from_folder(path=imagepath)
        .split_by_folder(train='train',valid='valid')
        .label_from_func(lambda o:groundtruth[o.name])
        .databunch(bs=32)
       )

The data loader does not load the images into memory at this point, rather it will be done on the fly during training process. However, when they are loaded (using the PIL library under the hood) they end up having 3 channels (RGB). We need to tell the loader that our images are greyscale and we want one channel. This is how that is done:

for itemList in ["train_dl", "valid_dl", "fix_dl", "test_dl"]:
   itemList = getattr(data, itemList)
   if itemList: itemList.x.convert_mode = "L"

TAKE NOTE How the data gets transformed by feeding it into the fastai PointsItemList.

On loading the data we transformed the particle co-ordinate from it's [-1, 1] scale to the pixel position of the particle center. And we reversed the order of the co-ordinates to (y,x) rather than (x,y) as we recorded them in the file.

We can then retrive the particle location information from the PointsItemList. This is how to access the 'labels' - in this case particle co-ordinates from the validation set for example:

pos=data.valid_ds[0][1].data.numpy() 
pos

array([[-0.008376,  0.404477]], dtype=float32)

These look to be back on a [-1,1] scale...

If we plot the image and the ground truth position we find out that the usual transform h/2 + x*(h/2) allows us to correctly position the dot, and that the cordinates are in the (y,x) order.

ax=data.valid_ds[0][0].show()
xy =data.valid_ds[0][1].data.numpy() 
h=51//2
_=plt.gca().plot([h+h*p for p in xy][0][1],[h+h*p for p in xy][0][0],'k.',lw=0)

Note that when I previously tried to feed untransformed co-ordinates into PointsItemList it resulted in an error. This is in contradiction to the documentation.

Load our Neural Net Architecture¶

Create a Learner and train the network¶

from deeptracktorch.model import deeptracknet2
display(deeptracknet2)

Sequential(
  (0): Conv2d(1, 16, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1))
  (1): ReLU()
  (2): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  (3): Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1))
  (4): ReLU()
  (5): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  (6): Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1))
  (7): ReLU()
  (8): MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0, dilation=1, ceil_mode=False)
  (9): Flatten()
  (10): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=32, bias=True)
  (11): ReLU()
  (12): Linear(in_features=32, out_features=32, bias=True)
  (13): ReLU()
  (14): Linear(in_features=32, out_features=2, bias=True)
)

Train the network¶

A Learner is a fastai concept [?] that combines data and model and provides functions to train the model.

learn = Learner(data, deeptracknet2)

learn.fit_one_cycle(10)

Make 'predictions' of particle position in test images¶

We extract the positions of paticles from images by using the predict method of our Learner. This takes an image as input and returns the models best guess at the y,x position of the particle in that image.

Let's examine a subset of the validation set.

learn.load('v1');

inspection_images = data.valid_ds[:10]

hs=51/2
f,ax=plt.subplots(2,5,figsize=(16,10))
for i in range(10):
    img = data.valid_ds[i][0]
    x,y = data.valid_ds[i][1].data.numpy()[0]
    x=hs+(x*hs)
    y=hs+(y*hs)
    
    p=learn.predict(img)
    xp = hs+(p[2][0]*hs)
    yp = hs+(p[2][1]*hs)
    
    img.show(ax=ax[i%2,i//2])
